The only thing I would trade for is an underfolder AK, a polish underfolder would be fantastic but manufacturer is not important. The only other way I would part with this AK is for an HK pistol like a USP .45 compact (my favorite) or a P2000. Don't care how used it is but if it's new and you want cash to boot, look elsewhere. I won't ask for cash if someone is willing to trade me an underfolder in similar condition to my AK even if it's an old WASR. title: For Sale:  Collectible Browning 4X Rimfire Rifle Scope
postcontent:
For sale is a collectible Browning 4X rimfire scope made by Redfield. I removed it from a 1971 model Browning BL-22 I purchased that was also in superb condition.  It has the ¾” tube and I left the attached rings in place.  I’m not a collector so I would like it to go to someone who can appreciate its collectible status.

This Browning 4x Rimfire scope was made between 1965 and 1976. FOV is 24 feet at 100 yards.  Evidently when these scopes were marketed under the Redfield name they were called the Sport-STER 4. The STER apparently stood for Standard Eye Relief.  The Browning ocular bell was smooth- not a serrated 3-ring design like Redfield.  Otherwise, it’s supposed to be the same scope.

The optics are clear and crisp and there is no damage of any kind to the gloss black finish.  The reticle cross hairs are a very fine target style.  There are no lens covers (I’ve never seen one with them).  Because I did not attempt to remove the rings I do not know if there are any mounting marks beneath them.  

The hard to find steel (not aluminum) rings are a very nice sturdy quality, nothing like the stuff you will find on the cheap scopes at Wally World.  Each side of the tube clamps has a recessed screw and each dovetail clamp has 2 screws for secure mounting.

The gold filled stamping on the reticle housing is nice and clear.  It consists of the magnification power, a serial number and the Browning name.  Both metal adjustment covers are also in excellent unmarked condition.  

The ocular bell diameter is 1.15” and the objective bell diameter is 1.10”.  Overall length is 9 1/8”.  The diminutive dimensions make for a really nice look on any rimfire and the optical quality with the fine cross hairs is on a par with newer scopes in this price range.

This scope looks to be in about a 98% condition.  You would be hard pressed to tell it from one that is NIB (well…except there is no box).

According to “Old Gunsights And Rifle Scopes” by Nick Stroebel (2008), the value was $150-$300 at publication.  As you might imagine, they are becoming more desirable as time passes and, when you can find them, they are currently selling for about $250 - $325.

title: For Sale:  Browning Hi-Power 9mm
postcontent:
For sale only. No trades.

For sale is an earlier model (pre 1970) Browning Hi-Power 9mm pistol. Comes with plastic case, manual, 2 14rd mags, Hogue grips, original honey colored wood grips.

All true Brownings are made by FN Herstal in Belgium. The earlier Brownings have the Made in Belgium rollmark only. Post 1970, Brownings were manufactured in Belgium and assembled in Portugal.
This pistol has the Made in Belgium rollmark only.

The slide, barrel, magazines, and all internal parts are Browning. The frame and slide stop lever are FEG. There were many instances in the earlier Brownings where the cast frames would crack and render the pistol useless. The only way to have a working gun, was to find a Browning frame, which was nearly impossible, or use a FEG frame, which has never had any issues with cracking. The pistol's lower price than usual Browning reflects this. The sights are custom made Millet type.

title: For Sale:  1942 Husqvarna Swedish Mauser 6.5X55 Excellent Condition
location: Arnold , St. Louis, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Husqvarna Mauser 6.5 X 55 Swedish 

This is the Swedish version of the German K98 8mm. The Swedish built rifle is made by none other than Husqvarna of the chainsaw fame. They started out building excellent weapons. Thier logo is still the H inside the muzzle end of a rifle with iron sights above it. 

This rifle is chambered in the 6.5x55 cartridge. Very easy and affordable to buy anywhere. This round can drop a deer easily so it's great for huinting. 

It appears to have never been fired! The bore has the deepest and most crisp lands and grooves that I've ever seen. I took it to the range and it punched out the center diamond of the bullseye right away.

The rifle is is excellent shape. There is a muzzle break installed onto the threaded barrel which seems to help with kick and climb. The original leather strap is included. This is a gorgeous piece of history that is still as functional as the day it was made.

I also have a Yugoslavian SKS 7.62 x 39 with the grenade launcher. There is a Tapco 20 rnd magazine and it's mounted in an ATI Dragonov stock. If you are interested in both rifles, I will combine the prices and cut a deal, just let me know.

1. Volquartsen MKII Hammer Bushing - Eliminates the magazine disconnect. This allows you to fire the pistol without a magazine, and also allows the magazine to eject like it should (it is too tight, and generally needs to be pulled out by hand even when released if this mod is not completed). Also makes the trigger pull a bit smoother, and lighter by decreasing friction.

2. Volquartsen Target Sear - Reduces trigger pull by a little over 1lb., and creates a shorter, faster, cleaner breaking pull.

3. Bolt Release "slingshot" modification - Allows the bolt lever to be released by gravity, and the bolt can be released by retracting it instead of pressing the bolt release.

A few other details...

Sights: Front fixed, Rear adjustable

Grips: Integral
Build Year: 2008
